<font color="#FF0000">THE LOVED LIVE IN OUR HEARTS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 19:23:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward,<br>
     I hardly know what to say.  My own daughter arrived on my 33rd birthday.  Her name was ready 7 years earlier during GLoria's and my engagement.  She's been both a joy and and an occasional trial, and she'll always have her own special place in my heart.<br>
     My oldest son tried to argue right of way with a subway train 5 years ago.  The train won of course, but since it was slowing down for a station, he survived, minus his lower right leg and foot.  It was a hell of a scare.  Afterwards, he said he said he hadn't realized how many people loved him and cared for him.<br>
     I wish I could find the words or whatever it takes to patch up the hole in your heart.  It doesn't get any easier when both parents and kids are older.  My maternal grandmother always missed her son, killed during the waning days of the Bulge, 2 weeks after making sergeant at age 19.<br>
When my Dad died suddenly at 49, his mother's doctor forbade her to attend the funeral because of her heart condition.  Both her and my grandfather found it hard that Dad died before them.  I hope you can someday find some joy in your memories of her; where she still lives as a little girl. 
